column11: Despite fierce resistance, Islamic State militants have reportedly been losing ground and equipment in Mosul since Iraqi government forces and US-led air forces launched a major campaign to recapture the city in October 2016 (Iraqi News, The Guardian, Asia Times, Politico). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

Time to resolve the question? Yes, some fighters are still holding out. Comparison class: after WWII ended and Japan officially surrenders, Japanese soldiers continued to not give up for decades. So what determines closure of this question, the Iraqi government's declaration that they have won the battle for Mosul, or when the last ISIS fighters die or surrender? Or when only a few dozed are still fighting? A handful?

In agreement with @wildwood2000 below. Although it is possible that IS forces could just collapse at any time, the probability is that they will not. Logically as IS retreats into a smaller and smaller area it will take longer for the attacking forces to capture each square metre. The area in Mosul controlled by IS seems to be (very roughly) reducing by about 10% to 15% a day, they are currently said to control 2 sq Km, My guess is that in a week they may hold between 1 sq Km and 0.75 sq Km, in 2 weeks 0.5 sq Km to 0.25 sq Km, 3 weeks 0.25 sq Km to 0.1 sq Km and after that it become more like a few terrorists holding some civilians hostage in a few buildings.

I am, however, perfectly willing to sacrifice my score on this Q if it means the folks in that town will have a couple fewer days of Perfectly Awful.

The IS Eid counter-attack is reported to have been only 20 or 30 fighters. it seems IS are not aiming to go for a mass suicide attack today. But the attack outside the Old City area shows that there are some IS fighters hidden in other parts of Mosul. How GJ will regard these small groups I am not sure. Presumably these hidden IS fighters could come out of hiding at any time in the next few weeks or months, so I assume GJ will consider Mosul "liberated" when Iraq says they have captured all the city even if odd outbreaks of fighting flare up later. It is still possible, but increasingly unlikely that the remaining 200 hundred IS fighters will surrender or be beaten by the end of June. 2 sq Km could take a while to clear one metre at a time.

The recent destruction of Al Nuri Grand Mosque suggests desperation by ISIS to deny Iraqi forces psychological victories. An estimated 500 ISIS fighters remain to defend the 0.7 sq mile area. Progress remains slow. However, Iraqi forces are close to opening up a corridor into the Old City for civilians to flee. With the Iraqui Army advancing and ISIS destroying the Al Nuri Mosque apparently due to the advance of the anti-islamic state forces, a retake becomes more likely to happen between July and September. (a)

Iraq had an objective of completing the retaking of Mosul by the end of Ramadan (24th or 25th June), but has previously missed its timing objected many times. The destroyed Mosque in very close the centre of the remaining area that IS control. Its destruction could be a sign that IS is almost finished (i.e. can only last a day or two) Its clear that now the end of IS in Mosul is close. Presumably the IS fighters that remain intend to be martyrs. It is not clear how many there are; estimates seem to suggest two or three hundred, but the estimates could be wrong. Its possible that some of martyrs are not as keen to die as others. Its possible that the last few could prefer to carry out a suicide attack, and so the battle will end quickly. It seems that IS still hold many thousands of hostages/human shields, at some point the IS fighters may be unable to keep control of them as they must be desperate not to killed by IS or in the cross fire (it is said many are in houses that have had their doors welded shut). So we have a situation where thousands of desperate people believe they and their families are at imminent risk of dying. Desperate people do unpredictable things. So this is long way of saying I have no idea when it will end, but it looks like days rather than months.

I listen when the US military goes on record. I give little credence to Middle Eastern military leaders. I found this helpful: Arab armies‚Äô problems certainly do not stem from want of money or equipment: the region‚Äôs countries allocate hefty shares of GDP for their forces (see map). The International Institute for Strategic Studies, a think-tank in London, reckons that countries in the Middle East and north Africa make up eight of the top 15 spenders on defence when measured as a share of the national pie. One problem is that much of this money is wasted. Billions are splurged on flashy gear like jet fighters or submarines that look impressive but may not be appropriate to the kinds of conflicts they are fighting. Such toys are also hard to maintain. And widespread theft and corruption mean that a lot of kit disappears, or is kept in the barracks (which is one reason why IS was able to nab so much in Iraq).

It's on:

Iraq's various military forces are organized like fiefdoms, making it difficult to coordinate military action. It recently announced a shift in strategy, signalling that the original strategy was not working as well as hoped. The new strategy essentially leaves the hardest task - the Old City - for last. The remaining ISIS fighters will be the most committed, most willing to sacrifice civilians, and least likely to surrender. Ramadan begins Saturday. I think it could put the offensive on "hold".

As Islamic State held neighbourhoods have fallen, morale and supplies fell with them. Furthermore, "Iraqi military engineers installed a new floating bridge across the Tigris river on Wednesday, reconnecting the two halves of Mosul to facilitate troop deployments ahead of a final assault to dislodge Islamic State"[1]. That, in conjunction with the fact that Jan Kubis (Special Representative for Iraq and Head of the United Nations Assistance Mission for Iraq) told the UN Security Council that "the liberation of the northern Iraqi city of Mosul "is imminent" and the days of ISIL's self-declared caliphate "are numbered""[2], makes me think that it's most likely that Mosul will be retaken by the end of June

I am assuming the US and western allies will not want to be seen to be killing civilians, which will limit how much advantage having complete control of the sky will be. The US (and western allies) will not want to be seen to be supporting ground troops that might not respect the Geneva Convention. Its pretty clear that in the age of mobile phone videos and 24/7 news coverage, and the use of the internet to get propaganda messages shown, that the sort of illegal behavour that soldiers used to get away with in wars a few year ago will come back to haunt the reputation of the military. Winning faster control of Mosul at the cost of reputational loss will not make America Great Again. History tends to remember the massacres and slaughter of civilians; particularly history as told in places like the middle east. So if anyone is planning to get long term peace, they had better avoid a Shia or Kurd on Sunni war crime. I think the military is very well aware of this. So my guess is that they will move slowly and carefully. I accept that the situation in Aleppo was different, but only a little. From reports it seems the civilian population initially supported ISIS, before (so they say) changing their minds when they saw how ISIS treated them. I doubt that the locals can do much except to try and hide or get out. Those locals who joined ISIS probably realize that if they put down their arms now they are probably not going to be any more likely to survive than if they keep fighting. In other wars lynch mobs are not kind to their fellow citizens who have occupied their city. While it might be possible to stop war crimes by organized troops, civilian revenge will still take place. The option for ISIS of retreating to Raqqa is not very attractive; they have to get there; and once there they know that they could face Russian and Syrian aim power that will not be so picky about collateral damage, as well as US air power. The ISIS leader will probably do what leaders usually do, try to run and hide, while foot soldiers make a futile stand. Of course I could be completely wrong and it will be over next week.
